abstract: Less than half of all Americans say President Donald Trump should be removed from office following his impeachment by the U.S. House of Representatives, according to a Reuters/Ipsos opinion poll released on Thursday, presenting a challenge for Democrats who will seek his ouster in a U.S. Senate trial.
snippet: Less than half of all Americans say President Donald Trump should be removed from office following his impeachment by the U.S. House of Representatives, according to a Reuters/Ipsos opinion poll released on Thursday, presenting a challenge for Dem...
lead_paragraph: NEW YORK — Less than half of all Americans say President Donald Trump should be removed from office following his impeachment by the U.S. House of Representatives, according to a Reuters/Ipsos opinion poll released on Thursday, presenting a challenge for Democrats who will seek his ouster in a U.S. Senate trial.
headline_main: Less Than Half of All Americans Want Trump Ousted Post-Impeachment: Reuters/Ipsos Poll
headline_print_headline: Less Than Half of All Americans Want Trump Ousted Post-Impeachment: Reuters/Ipsos Poll

abstract: House Speaker Nancy Pelosi's decision to delay sending the impeachment articles to the Senate risks eating further into senators' final weeks of campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination before the first caucus in February.
snippet: House Speaker Nancy Pelosi's decision to delay sending the impeachment articles to the Senate risks eating further into senators' final weeks of campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination before the first caucus in February.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Speaker Nancy Pelosi's decision to delay sending the impeachment articles to the Senate risks eating further into senators' final weeks of campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination before the first caucus in February.
headline_main: Presidential Hopefuls in Senate Say Impeachment Comes First
headline_print_headline: Presidential Hopefuls in Senate Say Impeachment Comes First

abstract: If hour one of Thursday’s debate was a substantive if sedate affair, hour two had significant and even sizzling moments.
snippet: If hour one of Thursday’s debate was a substantive if sedate affair, hour two had significant and even sizzling moments.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — If hour one of Thursday’s debate was a substantive if sedate affair, hour two had significant and even sizzling moments for Mayor Pete Buttigieg, Senator Elizabeth Warren and Senator Amy Klobuchar. Those three candidates are in a fierce battle in Iowa, where the leadoff presidential caucuses are just six and a half weeks away. Here are six takeaways from the December debate:

abstract: The House of Representatives voted to repeal the cap on a popular tax break, but the effort will die in the Senate.
snippet: The House of Representatives voted to repeal the cap on a popular tax break, but the effort will die in the Senate.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House voted on Thursday to temporarily eliminate a tax increase on some high-earning residents of states like California and New York that was included in President Trump’s 2017 tax overhaul, with some Republicans joining Democrats in support.

abstract: Putting his stamp on the top issue for Democratic voters, Michael Bloomberg on Thursday unveiled a health care plan that would expand coverage and cut people's costs by building on the current system, not replacing it.
snippet: Putting his stamp on the top issue for Democratic voters, Michael Bloomberg on Thursday unveiled a health care plan that would expand coverage and cut people's costs by building on the current system, not replacing it.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Putting his stamp on the top issue for Democratic voters, Michael Bloomberg on Thursday unveiled a health care plan that would expand coverage and cut people's costs by building on the current system, not replacing it.
headline_main: Bloomberg Health Plan Aims to Lower Costs, Cover More People
headline_print_headline: Bloomberg Health Plan Aims to Lower Costs, Cover More People

abstract: U.S. Democrats on Thursday pressed the Republican-controlled Senate to call Donald Trump's top lieutenants to testify in its trial of the impeached president, as they sought to focus attention on the trial ahead of the 2020 presidential election.
snippet: U.S. Democrats on Thursday pressed the Republican-controlled Senate to call Donald Trump's top lieutenants to testify in its trial of the impeached president, as they sought to focus attention on the trial ahead of the 2020 presidential election.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. Democrats on Thursday pressed the Republican-controlled Senate to call Donald Trump's top lieutenants to testify in its trial of the impeached president, as they sought to focus attention on the trial ahead of the 2020 presidential election.
headline_main: Democrats Seek High-Profile Trial for Trump in Senate
headline_print_headline: Democrats Seek High-Profile Trial for Trump in Senate

abstract: Rising Democratic candidate Pete Buttigieg came under attack during a debate among U.S. presidential hopefuls on Thursday, as his rivals questioned his lack of Washington experience and criticized his fundraising from wealthy donors.
snippet: Rising Democratic candidate Pete Buttigieg came under attack during a debate among U.S. presidential hopefuls on Thursday, as his rivals questioned his lack of Washington experience and criticized his fundraising from wealthy donors.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Rising Democratic candidate Pete Buttigieg came under attack during a debate among U.S. presidential hopefuls on Thursday, as his rivals questioned his lack of Washington experience and criticized his fundraising from wealthy donors.
headline_main: Wine Caves and Billionaires: Buttigieg Under Fire Over Fundraising at Democratic Debate
headline_print_headline: Wine Caves and Billionaires: Buttigieg Under Fire Over Fundraising at Democratic Debate

abstract: A new survey finds that Democrats haven’t fully embraced progressive policy proposals like free college and Medicare for all.
snippet: A new survey finds that Democrats haven’t fully embraced progressive policy proposals like free college and Medicare for all.
lead_paragraph: Progressive policy ideas have dominated the early stages of the Democratic primary campaign. But as candidates gather in Los Angeles for another debate on Thursday evening, Democratic voters may be seeking more moderate options.
